text: Hey Guys. Is everyone ready?
We will wait for five more minutes and  start.
Okay lets start.
Today we will be looking into regex (short for regular expressions) and some text manipulation commands
So does anyone know what regex is?
No
Okay well Regex is used to manipulate specific pieces of data based on a particular pattern that is specified.
So the regex command we will be covering today will be grep

Now what is grep? Well grep command is quite possibly the most common text processing command you will use. It allows you to search files for characters that match a certain pattern. What if you wanted to know if a file existed in a certain directory or if you wanted to see if a string was found in a file? It would be tedious to go through the file manually rather you can use the grep command to do the same
Now this would be hard to understand if you just read through my explanation. So lets do an example and see how the output comes out
Has everyone downloaded the textfile?
Okay so the syntax of the grep  command is as follows
egrep [command line options] <pattern> [path]
Now lets us do an example.Use cd to enter into the unix-smp directory
Has everyone done that?
<@UAMHTGNG0> uploaded a file: <https://ieeeunixsmp.slack.com/files/UAMHTGNG0/FAR17UN4R/-.sh|Untitled>

file.name: -.sh
file.title: Untitled
file.preview_highlight: egrep 'mellon' mysampledata.txt

text: Now execute the above command and tell me the output
Instead od my sampledata.txt it must be the text files name
in our case it is sammple.txt
*sample.txt
mellon in

Mark watermellons 12
Oliver rockmellons 2
is red
That is the right answer. The mellon is in a different color as it is the string that we tried to find in the text.
So has everyone executed it?
Well if you haven't quite got the answer it must come out to be something like the follows:
Mark watermelons 12
Oliver rockmellons 2
Nowfrom the above output what do understand the funtion of the above command is?
prints lines with the specified string in it?

Exactly. The basic behaviour of egrep is that it will print the entire line for every line which contains a string of characters matching the given pattern. This is important to note, we are not searching for a word but a string of characters.

Also note that we included the pattern within quotes. This is not always required but it is safer to get in the habit of always using them. They are required if your pattern contains characters which have a special meaning on the command line.
Is everyone clear with everything till here?
does this involve special characters like spaces too? As in, can we use this command to look for double spaces in the text?
Yes absolutely.That is why we enclose them in quotes as mentioned below
Okay now execute the following command.

from which the pattern is found

So as you can see from the output sometimes we want to know not only which lines matched but their line number as well.
Then we use the above command.

text: And what do you get?
it gives the number of occurrences of the pattern 'mellon'
You get the number of times the word is repeated
Yes exactly. You are absolutely right.
So as Sachith and Abhinav pointed out,the above command is used when we are not interested in seeing the matched lines but wish to know how many lines did match.
what happens if the string occurs twice in a single line?
The line will be displayed regardless. And both the occurances will be higlighted. Try it out yourself when you get the time.

text: What  do you get?
No output
Yes true.And why do you think that happens since there is the string mark  in the text file, so shouldn't it be displayed?
we have put in mark and not Mark
As Abhinav mentioned there is no output regardless of the string being in the textfile
Yes. That is the reason
Now the reason being is that the command is case sensitive and will search for the string just as as how we have inputed it. So, does anyone have any idea asto how we can mitigate this problem?
You understood the above question?
do you mean how we can make the search case insensitive
maybe by using an option
Yes
using '-i'?

text: Yes exactly. Correct answer Anusha
locates mark in the text file irrespective of the case of any of the letters

Yes exactly. We might sometimes want to find a particular string for example the  no of occurrences of the word 'the' in the textfile. Then we must search for all the words regardless of its  case and thus in such a situation we use the above command
With that we have come to end about <http://grep.Is|grep.Is> everything clear till now?
Okay then. Now we shall learn about pipes and tee command
How many of you know what a pipe command is?

OK thats fine . Ill explain. The pipe operator |, represented by a vertical bar, allows us to get the stdout of a command and make that the stdin to another process. Basically it uses the output of one process as input of the other
Okay now we will do an example to understand better.
You guys are familiar with the cat command right?

Okay now we will  go into the tee command.
Now the tee command is used if I wanted to write the output of my command to two different streams
Now open a directory in terminal that has multiple files in it.
Tell me when you are done with that.

text: And tell me what you get
It listed the files in that directory
Open up the sample.txt also after executing. You will understand then
Is that the only thing you noticed?
the contents on sample.txt have been replaced with the list of files

You should see the output of ls on your screen and if you open up the sample.txt file you should see the same information. So tee has set its output to two streams whereas if you just use piping it will only send it to one stream
Thats right.
So thats basically what tee and pipe is. any doubts?
i didnt understand what the two streams are
it just copied the result of ls onto the file
As in the output is not given just to the terminal. It is also sent to the text file. The text file is one output stream and the editor is the other.
